{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654981"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:58:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:58:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18645"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18645"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.27,0.42,0,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77705"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11377"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63218"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6700"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26839"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77705"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe venous drainage of inferior cerebral structures follows a hierarchical pattern, with smaller veins joining to form larger vessels that ultimately drain into the dural venous sinuses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary drainage pathway for deep cerebral structures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drains into transverse sinus","Internal cerebral veins to great cerebral vein","Drains into cavernous sinus","Drains via superficial cortical veins","Drains into superior sagittal sinus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal cerebral veins to great cerebral vein\u003C/strong\u003E represents the main drainage pathway for deep cerebral structures. The paired internal cerebral veins join to form the great cerebral vein (of Galen), which then merges with the inferior sagittal sinus to form the straight sinus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into transverse sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The transverse sinus receives blood from other dural sinuses rather than directly from cerebral veins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into cavernous sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The cavernous sinus receives blood from the ophthalmic veins and superficial middle cerebral vein\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains via superficial cortical veins\u003C/strong\u003E - These drain the cerebral cortex and superficial white matter, not deep structures\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into superior sagittal sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - This primarily receives drainage from superior cerebral veins and superficial cortical areas\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe internal cerebral veins receive tributaries from the choroid plexus, thalamus, and basal ganglia. The basal vein (of Rosenthal) also joins the great cerebral vein, bringing drainage from inferior cerebral surfaces.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The great cerebral vein (of Galen) drains deep cerebral structures and joins with the inferior sagittal sinus to form the straight sinus.","The internal cerebral veins drain the deep white matter and basal ganglia before joining to form the great cerebral vein.","The basal vein (of Rosenthal) drains the inferior surfaces of the cerebral hemispheres and joins the great cerebral vein."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63218"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18645"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63218"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T22:29:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T22:31:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11377"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77705"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardio